# TEAM BRIEFING — NetPulse, Round 1

Read Parts 1–5 before you touch the script. If four people understand the project the same
way, the presentation holds together even when someone forgets a line. If they don't, the
panel finds out in the first question.

**Parts 1–5** = understanding. **Part 6** = the script. **Part 7** = the questions they'll ask.

---
---

# PART 1 — The basics

## 1.1 What is SNMP?

**Simple Network Management Protocol.** It is the language network devices use to report
how they are doing.

Think of a hospital ward. Every patient has a chart hanging at the end of the bed with
numbered lines on it — line 1 temperature, line 2 pulse, line 3 blood pressure. A nurse walks
around every hour, reads the numbers off each chart, and writes them into a central register.

That's SNMP.

- The **patient** is a switch, router or firewall.
- The **chart** is called the **MIB** (Management Information Base) — the list of everything
  the device is willing to report about itself.
- Each **numbered line** on the chart is an **OID** (Object Identifier) — a unique address
  for one specific measurement. Real OIDs look like `1.3.6.1.2.1.2.2.1.14`, which is why
  everyone uses the human names instead.
- The **nurse** is the **manager** (the monitoring server). It asks; the device answers.
- The small piece of software on the device that answers is the **agent**.
- The nurse's hourly round is **polling** — the manager asks, on a schedule.
- If the patient collapses, they don't wait for the nurse. They shout. That's a **trap** —
  the device pushes an alert to the manager on its own.

Two directions, then: **polling** is pull (manager asks every 30 seconds), **traps** are push
(device shouts when something breaks). Almost all real monitoring is polling, because a device
that has died cannot send a trap.

### Why SNMP matters

It is universal. Cisco, HPE, Juniper, Arista, an old unmanaged switch in a cupboard — they all
speak it. That's why a monitoring tool built on SNMP works across a mixed vendor network, and
it's why the problem statement names it.

### The five OIDs we use

| Name | Plain meaning | What it catches |
|---|---|---|
| `ifInErrors` | Count of corrupted packets arriving on an interface | Bad cable, dying optic, duplex mismatch |
| `hrProcessorLoad` | CPU utilisation | Overload, routing churn, a process spinning |
| `hrStorageUsed` | Memory in use | Memory leaks, buffer exhaustion |
| `sysUpTime` | How long since the device last booted | Silent reboots — the number resets |
| `ifOperStatus` | Is the interface up or down | Link failure |

Note `ifInErrors` is a **counter** — it only goes up, and it never resets until reboot. So the
interesting thing is never the value, it's the **rate**: 400 errors is meaningless, 400 errors
*per minute and climbing* is a failing link. Remember this, it comes back in Part 3.

### One thing we should say honestly

Our demo replays recorded data instead of polling live devices. **The schema is real** — every
metric travels under the real OID names above — but the source is a file, not a switch. Part 4
explains why, and it is a good reason, not an excuse.

---

## 1.2 What the problem statement actually asks for

> *"Network administrators managing large device fleets need a consolidated view of device
> health that goes beyond simple up/down status. Poll devices using SNMP, aggregate multiple
> health metrics per device, and compute a composite health score using a weighted formula or
> trained regression model. Present a web-based inventory view with color-coded health
> indicators and per-metric drill-down."*

Broken into parts:

1. Collect metrics from devices over SNMP
2. Combine several metrics per device into one health score
3. Show it in a web dashboard, colour-coded, with drill-down per metric

**The real problem underneath it:** an admin with 500 devices opens a dashboard and sees 500
green dots. One of those devices is going to fail tonight. Nothing on the screen tells them which.

Up/down monitoring can't help, because all three of the failures that actually hurt look
perfectly healthy to it:

- **Slow memory leak** — device stays UP for days, memory creeps up 2% an hour, dies at 3am Sunday.
- **Interface error creep** — link is UP, but errors are climbing. Users experience lag and
  retransmits long before anything is officially "down".
- **Silent reboot loop** — the device reboots every few hours. Every poll finds it UP. The
  dashboard is green the entire time.

That's the gap. Everything we built aims at it.

---

## 1.3 Why we did NOT just use a weighted formula

The brief suggests: `score = 0.4 × CPU + 0.3 × memory + 0.2 × errors + 0.1 × uptime`.

Two problems.

**First, the weights are indefensible.** Why 0.4 and not 0.35? Nobody can answer. We picked
them, so they're an opinion wearing the costume of a measurement.

**Second and worse — a raw number ignores what's normal for that device.** A core switch that
normally runs at 70% CPU is fine at 70%. An access switch that normally sits at 12% is in
serious trouble at 40%. One shared formula calls the healthy device sick and the sick device
healthy.

**So what did we do with it?** We implemented it anyway and display it as a second column
beside our score. It's our baseline, not our product. That gives us a demo moment: a device the
weighted formula calls "68, fine" while NetPulse flags it critical — because it has drifted far
from *its own* normal and has 15 devices sitting downstream of it.

**The line to remember:** *"The brief's weighted formula is our baseline, not our product. We
implement it, display it, and beat it."*

---
---

# PART 2 — What we're proposing

## 2.1 The core idea: three signals, not one score

A health score of 41 tells an operator a device is unwell. It does not tell them whether to get
out of bed. So we compute three separate things and multiply them.

| Signal | The question | How we get it | Example output |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Health** | How bad is it? | Model learns this device's own normal, measures the deviation | `24 / 100` |
| **Urgency** | How long have I got? | Draw the trend line forward to the critical threshold | `~4 hours` |
| **Impact** | What breaks with it? | Walk the network map to count everything downstream | `15 devices` |

`priority = health × urgency × impact`

**Why multiply?** Because a nearly-dead device with nothing behind it is a low priority, and a
mildly-degraded core switch with 15 devices behind it is a high one. Multiplication makes any
one signal able to dominate — which is what you want. Addition would let a big Impact hide a
perfect Health score, and the device would rank high while being completely fine.

**"Independent" matters.** The three come from three unrelated sources — a model, a trend line,
a graph. If one is wrong, the other two still stand. The weighted formula is the opposite: one
number, and if the weights are wrong, everything downstream of it is wrong.

**The one-liner:** *"We don't just score health — we tell you what will fail, when, and what
breaks with it."*

## 2.2 The seven features, in plain words

| | Feature | What it does | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A** | **Self-baseline anomaly detection** | Each device learns its own normal. We flag deviation from *that*, not from a shared threshold. | **BUILT & VALIDATED** |
| **B** | **Blast-radius impact** | Walk the topology: "if core-sw-01 dies, these 15 devices go dark." Turns a health score into a business consequence. | Designed · 21–23 Jul |
| **C** | **Time-to-failure forecast** | Extend the trend line to where it crosses critical. "~4 hours" instead of "it's red now." | Designed · 24–26 Jul |
| **D** | **Peer comparison** | Compare a device only to its same-role, same-site siblings. "Errors 8.2× higher than its 11 peer switches" — same config, same job, so an outlier means bad hardware or bad config. | Designed · 21–23 Jul |
| **F** | **Explainability** | Every score says why. "Memory pressure drives 71% of this score." An unexplained score doesn't get acted on. | Designed · 24–26 Jul |
| **G** | **What-if failure map** | Click any device: "if this fails, here's what goes with it." Planning tool, not just an alarm. | Designed · 27–28 Jul |
| **H** | **Correlated alert suppression** | Parent fails → 15 children also alarm. We recognise one cause, suppress 15 child alerts, raise one incident. | Designed · 27–28 Jul |

*(There is no E — the register skipped it and we kept the letters stable rather than renumber
files. If asked, say exactly that.)*

**If you remember one feature, remember D.** Peer comparison is the one reviewers underestimate.
Comparing a device against identical siblings is what separates *"this device is busy"* from
*"this device is broken."*

## 2.3 How the pieces fit together

```
NAB data  →  replay engine  →  scoring core  →  Supabase  →  Next.js console
             (pluggable         health, urgency,   Postgres +    priority list,
              collector,        impact, remedy     realtime      charts, blast map
              SNMP-native)      lookup
```

Two design points carry marks:

**The swap-in guarantee.** Every metric moves under its real SNMP name through a *pluggable
collector*. Replace the replay collector with a live `pysnmp` poller and nothing downstream
changes. The schema is real; only the source is simulated.

**Topology is an input, not decoration.** One graph powers blast radius, the what-if map and
alert suppression. Three features out of one data structure — which is why they land in the
same week rather than three separate weeks.

