# PART 3 — The technical bits, explained simply

This part is why we win the feasibility marks. Everyone should be able to explain 3.2 and 3.5.

## 3.1 What is an "anomaly"?

A reading that doesn't fit the device's own pattern. Not "high" — *unusual for this device*.

A night-shift worker sleeping at noon isn't an anomaly. You sleeping at noon might be. Same
behaviour, different baseline. That single idea is the whole project.

## 3.2 Method 1 — the classical threshold (3-sigma)

The traditional approach, and the one we had to beat.

1. Take all readings from a device. Compute the average.
2. Compute the standard deviation — a measure of how much the readings normally bounce around.
3. Flag anything more than 3 standard deviations from the average.

**Analogy.** If your commute is normally 30 minutes and swings by about 5, then 3-sigma says
anything past 45 minutes is unusual. Sensible. Cheap. No machine learning.

**And it works well.** We must be honest about this — it beat our model twice. On a single
metric it's close to the best you can do, because "far from the average" is exactly what a
single-metric anomaly *is*.

**Where it breaks:** it needs a decent amount of variation to calibrate against. A device whose
readings barely move has a tiny standard deviation, so 3-sigma is either paranoid or blind.
In our run 2, `acc-sw-01` flagged **zero** times and missed its real anomaly completely, while
`dist-sw-01` flagged **180** times to catch 2 real ones. One rule, both failure modes at once.

## 3.3 Method 2 — Isolation Forest

An unsupervised model. "Unsupervised" means nobody tells it what an anomaly looks like; it
works it out from the shape of the data.

**Analogy — twenty questions.** Imagine identifying one person in a crowd by asking yes/no
questions. For an average person you need many questions: are they tall, are they wearing a
coat, do they have a bag… For someone genuinely unusual — a person on stilts — one question
does it. *Unusual things are easy to isolate.*

Isolation Forest does exactly that, numerically. It slices the data with random cuts and counts
how many cuts it takes to fence off each point. Points that get isolated in very few cuts are
the anomalies.

**Why bother, if 3-sigma is simpler?** Because 3-sigma can only ever ask *"is this number far
from average?"* Isolation Forest can consider several things at once — the value, how fast it's
changing, how far it's drifted, how jumpy it's been — and find combinations that are unusual
even when no single number looks alarming. That's how you catch a memory leak: no reading is
extreme, but the *combination* of steady rise with no plateau is.

## 3.4 The hidden variable nobody talks about: what is "normal" measured over?

This was our biggest discovery, and it's a genuinely good talking point.

The 3-sigma arithmetic never changed across our experiments. What changed was the window it
was calculated over:

| "Normal" measured over | Recall |
|---|---|
| The entire 14-day stream | 76% |
| Only the first 15% of the stream, then frozen | 84% |
| A rolling 24-hour window that moves with the device | 88% |

**Same three lines of arithmetic. Three different answers.**

So a "static threshold" isn't one method — it's a formula *plus* a hidden choice, and that
choice matters more than the formula. Which is exactly the argument for letting each device
learn and continuously update its own baseline instead of us picking a window by hand.

**Why the frozen baseline failed:** networks drift. Traffic patterns change, new users come on,
software gets updated. A baseline learned in week one is wrong by week two, so everything looks
anomalous. On `acc-sw-04` it flagged 3,088 of 3,428 rows — 90% of the data called abnormal.
That's not detection, that's noise.

## 3.5 Recall and flag rate — why we always quote both

**Recall** = of the real anomalies, what fraction did we catch? 23 out of 24 = 96%.

**Flag rate** = what fraction of all readings did we raise an alert on? 1,039 of ~55,000 = 1.9%.

**Recall alone is a lie, and we can prove it.** In one of our runs we hit 84% recall — by
flagging 90% of all rows. A system that alerts on almost everything will "catch" almost every
anomaly. It is also completely useless.

**Analogy.** A doctor who diagnoses every single patient with flu will correctly identify 100%
of flu cases. Perfect recall, worthless doctor.

**So: matched alert budget.** In our final test, each device's alert budget is set to *that
device's own* 3-sigma flag rate. The model is allowed to raise exactly as many alerts as the
classical method — not one more — and must choose its most suspicious points to spend them on.

Result: **96% vs 88%, at an identical 1.9% flag rate.** Because the budgets are equal, the
difference is detection *quality*, not alert volume. This is the most important sentence in the
whole presentation.

## 3.6 Derived features — why the model lost, then won

When we first matched the budgets, **our model lost**: 83% against 3-sigma's 88%.

**Why.** We were feeding Isolation Forest a single column — just the value. On one dimension
there is nothing to isolate *with*. The only question available is "is this number far from the
others," which is precisely what 3-sigma does, more directly and with less overhead. 3-sigma
deserved to win, and it did.

**The fix.** Give the model dimensions worth having. From the same raw stream we compute:

| Feature | Meaning | The failure it exposes |
|---|---|---|
| `value` | the raw reading | outright spikes |
| `delta` | change since the last reading | sudden jumps |
| `deviation` | distance from the recent rolling average | slow drift away from normal |
| `volatility` | how jumpy the recent window has been | instability, flapping |

Now the model can spot a point that is *individually unremarkable* but whose combination is
wrong — rising steadily, drifting from its own average, with no volatility. That combination is
a memory leak, and it is invisible to any single-number rule.

Result: 96%, at the same alert budget. **The model won when it was given something to reason
with, not when it was given a bigger megaphone.**

All four features are **trailing-only** — computed from past readings, never future ones. If we
used future data the result would be worthless in production. Worth saying aloud if pushed.

**Crucially, we did NOT improve the 3-sigma baseline.** It stays on the raw value alone,
exactly as a real ops team would run it. Improving your own opponent makes the comparison
meaningless.

## 3.7 Blast radius — how the network map works

`topology.json` holds 20 devices, each with a `parent`. That's a tree.

```
core-sw-01
 ├─ dist-sw-01 ─ acc-sw-01, acc-sw-02, acc-sw-03
 ├─ dist-sw-02 ─ acc-sw-04, acc-sw-05, acc-sw-06, ap-ctrl-01
 ├─ fw-01
 └─ rtr-edge-01
```

If `core-sw-01` fails, everything beneath it loses its path. Counting the descendants gives 15.
That's the Impact signal — a graph walk, using `networkx`, about ten lines of code.

The same tree gives us the what-if map (feature G) and alert suppression (feature H): if the
parent is failing and 15 children alarm at the same moment, that isn't 16 problems, it's one.

**Why 20 devices and 4 tiers matters.** Real enterprise networks are built in layers — core in
the middle, distribution feeding buildings or floors, access where users plug in, plus edge
routers, firewalls and a wireless controller. Our naming follows that convention exactly. It
signals to an HPE panel that we modelled a real network rather than inventing `device1, device2`.

