# PART 4 — Done, not done, next

Be exact about this. **Claiming more than we've built is the fastest way to lose Initial
Progress marks**, because a panelist only has to ask one follow-up to find out.

## Built and working today

- Full detection pipeline — 6 experiment scripts, all runnable from the repo
- `rolling_features_eval.py` — the final result, 96% vs 88% at matched budget, verified against
  human-labelled ground truth
- `topology.json` — 20 devices, 4 tiers, complete parent/child graph
- `device_map.json` — 15 devices mapped to 15 real data streams
- `docs/mockup.html` — the full console. Real working HTML, not an image
- `docs/REMEDIES.md` — 12-rule symptom → cause → action table
- `architecture.svg`, `README.md` with full results, public GitHub repo

## Designed and mocked, not yet built

Features B, C, D, F, G, H. All visible in the mockup, all with dates on the slide.

**Say it in these words:** *"A is built and validated. B through H are designed, mocked and
scheduled."* That's a complete answer and it is true.

## Between now and 31 July

| Dates | Work |
|---|---|
| 21–23 Jul | Collector + scoring service live on Supabase; blast radius (B) and peer comparison (D) — both come straight out of the topology graph, so they're the cheapest real features |
| 24–26 Jul | Next.js console wired to realtime; React Flow map; forecast (C) and explainability (F) |
| 27–28 Jul | Detector bakeoff — LOF, One-Class SVM, ensemble; what-if map (G); alert suppression (H) |
| 29–30 Jul | Freeze, final README, rehearsal — **code complete a day early** |
| 31 Jul | Live demo |

**Why the detector bakeoff is scheduled late, not early.** The detector is a swappable component
behind a fixed interface: anything that takes a stream and returns flagged points drops into the
same slot. So nothing else in the build waits on which model wins. That's deliberate architecture,
not procrastination — and it's a good answer if someone asks why we haven't finished choosing.

## Why the demo replays data instead of polling live devices

Two reasons, both worth saying:

1. **Healthy devices produce nothing to detect.** Polling a lab switch that is working fine gives
   us no anomalies and no labels. We could not put an honest accuracy number on anything.
2. **Replay is reproducible.** Same data, same result, every single run. On demo day that's a
   feature, not a compromise — nothing depends on a device misbehaving on cue.

And architecturally it doesn't matter, because of the swap-in guarantee in 2.3.

