# PART 5 — What we achieved, and what went wrong on the way

The route is the story. **Do not present the 96% as if it arrived on the first try** — it's more
convincing *because* of what came before it.

## The six experiments

| # | What we tried | Result | What happened |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Isolation Forest on the full stream | 88% | Looked great. Was cheating — trained and scored on the same data, so it had already seen the answers. |
| 2 | Classical 3-sigma, full stream | 76% | Lower recall, but the *behaviour* was the finding: blind on quiet devices, screaming on noisy ones. |
| 3 | Proper temporal split, both methods | 84% / 84% | A dead tie — because both had degenerated into flagging nearly everything. **This taught us to always report flag rate.** |
| 4 | Rolling 24h baseline, both methods | 92% / 88% | We won, but with 3× the alerts. Not a clean win, so we didn't claim it. |
| 5 | Matched the alert budgets | 83% / 88% | **We lost.** The model was fed one column and had nothing to isolate with. |
| 6 | Added derived features, kept budgets matched | **96% / 88%** | Won properly, at an identical flag rate. |

## The two bugs worth mentioning

Both are good answers to "what was hard?", because they show we actually read our output
instead of trusting the summary line.

**Bug 1 — we accidentally silenced our own demo device.** Budgets were rounded to whole
numbers, and `core-sw-01`'s budget rounded down to **zero**. The most important device on the
network was given permission to raise no alerts at all — and the totals line still looked fine.
Fixed with a floor of one flag per chunk.

**Bug 2 — flat data blew the budget.** When a metric is perfectly flat, many points score
identically. Our code flagged every tie, so `srv-mon-01` raised 542 alerts against a budget of
107 — five times over, silently. Fixed with exact rank selection.

**The lesson under both:** the totals line looked reasonable in both cases. We only caught them
by reading the per-device table. That's a genuinely good thing to say to an engineering panel.

## What we're proud of

- Everything is validated against **someone else's labels**, not ours
- Every run is still in the repo, **including the two we lost**
- Every number is quoted with its flag rate
- We know exactly what we haven't built, and it's written down

## Known limitations (say them before you're asked)

- **We miss 1 of 24 windows.** It sits in a low-variance stretch where the anomaly is small
  relative to the device's own noise floor. We could catch it by widening the budget — that's
  exactly the trade we refuse to make quietly.
- **Isolation Forest is a baseline, not a verdict.** LOF, One-Class SVM and an ensemble get
  tested before the 31st.
- **Root causes are written by us, not learned.** Our dataset labels *when* things went wrong,
  never *why*. No public dataset labels causes. So detection is validated; diagnosis is
  engineered. We keep those two claims apart deliberately.
- **One metric per device today.** Expanding to 3–4 per device is the only planned data change.
- **Not load-tested.** We chose 15 devices so we could validate accuracy properly rather than
  quote a scale number nobody had checked.

