Nine slides, roughly 8 minutes. Split the slides among yourselves.

These are speaking lines, not lines to memorise word for word. Say them in your own voice, but
keep the **bolded** phrases exactly — those are the ones that do the work.

---

### Slide 1 — Title

> NetPulse. The problem statement asks for a device health scorer, and we want to be upfront
> about how we read that.
>
> A health score tells an operator a device is sick. It doesn't tell them whether to get out of
> bed at 3am. So we built something that answers the question underneath it: **what will fail,
> when, and what breaks with it.**
>
> Four numbers, then we'll earn them. **96% recall against real human-labelled anomalies.**
> 20 devices across a proper four-tier topology. Three independent signals instead of one
> weighted guess. And zero invented failures — every anomaly we detect was labelled by somebody
> else, before we ever saw it.
>
> The repo is public and on screen. Everything we claim today, you can clone and run.

*Pause after "zero invented failures." Let it land — most teams cannot say it.*

---

### Slide 2 — Problem understanding

> Three failures that up/down monitoring cannot see.
>
> A **memory leak** — the device stays UP for days while memory creeps up two percent an hour,
> and it dies at 3am on a Sunday. **Interface error creep** — the link is UP, but errors are
> climbing, and users are already feeling it. **A silent reboot loop** — the device restarts
> every few hours, and every single poll catches it UP. The dashboard is green throughout.
>
> Now the awkward part, and we'd rather raise it than have you raise it. The brief suggests a
> weighted formula. We can't defend one. Why is CPU nought point four and memory nought point
> three? We picked them — that's an opinion dressed up as a measurement.
>
> And a raw score ignores what's normal *for that device*. A core switch that always runs at 70%
> CPU is fine at 70%. An access switch that normally sits at 12% is in trouble at 40%. One shared
> formula calls the healthy device sick and the sick device healthy.
>
> At the bottom are the three questions an operator actually asks. **A health score answers none
> of them.**

---

### Slide 3 — Proposed solution

> So we compute three things instead of one, and each one answers a question.
>
> **Health** — how bad is it? A model learns each device's own baseline and measures deviation
> from *that*. No shared thresholds, no weights to defend.
>
> **Urgency** — how long have I got? We extend the trend to where it crosses critical. Four
> hours, not "it's red now."
>
> **Impact** — what breaks with it? A walk over the topology graph. Fifteen devices go dark if
> this one fails.
>
> Multiply them, and you get that line: **priority 98, core-sw-01, four hours to critical,
> fifteen devices downstream, memory driving 71% of it.** That is a sentence an operator can act
> on at 3am. A score of 24 is not.
>
> Multiplication rather than addition, deliberately — a nearly-dead device with nothing behind it
> should stay low, and a mildly-degraded core switch with fifteen devices behind it should jump
> to the top.
>
> And on the competition — SolarWinds, PRTG and Nagios all give you a health score. **None of them
> rank by blast radius, forecast time to failure, or collapse an alert storm.** We're not claiming
> to beat them on polling scale. We're claiming a different output.

---

### Slide 4 — Data strategy

> This slide exists to kill one question before it's asked: *you invented your own anomalies, so
> of course you detect them.*
>
> We didn't. The metrics are the **Numenta Anomaly Benchmark** — real AWS server telemetry with
> anomaly windows labelled by humans and published by someone else. Fifteen devices, about four
> thousand readings each, sixty thousand real data points, fourteen days per stream, twenty-five
> labelled windows. **We are graded against somebody else's answer key.**
>
> On the right is how it physically reaches the score: a real stream per device, replayed at
> thirty times speed, emitted under real SNMP object names — ifInErrors, hrProcessorLoad,
> hrStorageUsed, sysUpTime — into the scoring core.
>
> Now the two limits, from us rather than from you. **The topology is synthetic** — no public
> dataset ships a network graph alongside labelled telemetry. And five of the twenty devices
> replay time-offset copies purely to populate that graph; **they're excluded from every recall
> number we quote.** Fifteen devices carry real independent streams.
>
> And why we replay instead of polling live on demo day: a healthy lab switch gives us nothing to
> detect and nothing to be judged against. Replay gives you a reproducible failure with a known
> right answer.

---

### Slide 5 — Architecture

> Left to right. Real labelled telemetry, replayed through a pluggable collector, into a scoring
> core that does anomaly detection, forecasting and graph analysis, out to Supabase, which pushes
> realtime updates into a Next.js console.
>
> Two decisions carry the weight here.
>
> **The swap-in guarantee.** Every metric travels under its real SNMP object name. Swap the
> replay collector for a live pysnmp poller and one class changes and nothing downstream does.
> The schema is real; only the source is simulated.
>
> **Topology is an input, not decoration.** One graph powers blast radius, the what-if map and
> alert suppression — **three features out of one data structure**, which is why they land in the
> same week instead of three separate ones.
>
> Power BI isn't in the build. Scores land in Postgres so BI tools attach directly, and we'd
> rather call that export-ready than claim an integration we haven't written.

---

