### Slide 7 — Technical feasibility

*Slow down. This is the slide that decides the round.*

> That's a real terminal, on our machine, and the script is in the repo.
>
> The headline: **given derived features and an equal alert budget, self-baselining detection
> catches two failures the classical threshold misses. 96% against 88%, at an identical 1.9%
> flag rate.**
>
> The phrase that matters is **matched alert budget**. Each device's budget is set to that
> device's *own* 3-sigma flag rate — the model may raise exactly as many alerts as the classical
> method and not one more. 1,039 flags against 1,023. So the recall difference is **detection
> quality, not us shouting louder**.
>
> And the boundary, before you ask for it. Recall on its own is gameable, and we can prove it —
> one of our earlier runs hit 84% recall by flagging 90% of all rows. That result is still in the
> repo. Which is why **every number we quote in this deck carries its flag rate beside it**.
>
> Isolation Forest is a validated baseline, not our final answer. LOF, One-Class SVM and an
> ensemble get benchmarked against the same labels before the 31st.

---

### Slide 8 — How we got to 96%

*The point of this slide is credibility. Deliver it with some enjoyment — it's a good story.*

> The 96% is only worth anything if you can see where it came from. Six experiments.
>
> Run one was our first proof of concept — 88%, and it was cheating. It trained and scored on the
> same data, so it had already seen the answers.
>
> Run two, the classical threshold, 76%. The interesting part wasn't the recall, it was the
> behaviour: one global rule was **blind on quiet devices and screaming on noisy ones**. One
> device flagged zero times and missed its real anomaly entirely. Another flagged 180 times to
> catch two.
>
> Run three added a proper temporal split, and the two methods **tied** at 84% — because both had
> degenerated into flagging almost everything. That gave us the rule we've followed since:
> **recall alone is gameable. Always report the flag rate beside it.**
>
> Run four made the baseline roll with the device. We caught one more window, but raised three
> times the alerts. Not a clean win, so we didn't claim it.
>
> Run five is the one we're most glad to show you. We matched the alert budgets — **and our model
> lost. 83 against 88.** The diagnosis: we'd been feeding it a single column, and on one dimension
> there is nothing to isolate with. Three-sigma was the better tool and it correctly won.
>
> Run six fixed the actual problem. Give the model dimensions worth reasoning about — rate of
> change, drift from its own average, volatility — and hold it to each device's own budget.
> **96 against 88, same flag rate.**
>
> And the thing we learned that we didn't expect: a static threshold isn't one method. It's a
> formula **plus a hidden choice of what "normal" is measured over.** The same three lines of
> arithmetic gave us 76, 84 and 88 percent depending only on that choice. Which is the whole
> argument for letting every device learn its own.
>
> **If you're wondering whether we tuned until we liked the number — the classical method matched
> or beat us twice first, and both of those losses are committed in the repo.**

---

### Slide 9 — Plan, team, demo

> On the left, what you can clone right now — the repo, all six experiment scripts including the
> two we lost, the topology, and the working console mockup.
>
> On the right, the sequence to the 31st. The ordering is deliberate: **blast radius and peer
> comparison come first because both fall straight out of the topology graph we've already
> built** — cheapest real features we have. The detector bakeoff sits late on purpose, because
> the detector is a swappable component behind a fixed interface, so nothing else in the build
> waits on which model wins.
>
> The line that matters: **code complete on the 30th, a day early.** The 31st is rehearsal, not
> scrambling.
>
> Four of us, one owner per layer, and every member can speak to any slide in this deck.
>
> And the demo. Fifteen devices replaying healthy at thirty times speed. We trigger a real
> anomaly sequence on core-sw-01, and inside about **thirty-five seconds** you'll watch it slide
> amber, jump to the top of the priority list with a four-hour forecast and fifteen downstream
> devices, light up the blast map, and **collapse fifteen child alerts into one incident.**
>
> Which is the whole thing in one sentence: **we don't just score health — we tell you what will
> fail, when, and what breaks with it.**

*Stop there. Don't add a thank-you paragraph.*

