# PART 7 — The questions they will ask

**Rules:** whoever presented the slide answers the question. Nobody adds "and also…" unless
handed off. If nobody knows — *"we don't know, we'd have to test it"* — then stop talking.

---

**Q1. "The brief asked for a weighted formula. You didn't do it."**

We did — it's displayed as a second column beside our score. What we didn't do is *rely* on it.
It requires us to defend why CPU is 0.4 and memory 0.3, and nobody can. And a raw score ignores
that a switch idling at 70% may be normal while one at 40% is broken. It's our baseline, not our
product. We implement it, display it, and beat it.

---

**Q2. "Did you just tune until you liked the number?"** ← *the dangerous one*

The opposite happened. The classical threshold matched or beat us twice first. Run 3 tied at 84%.
In run 5 we matched the alert budgets and our model lost, 83 to 88. Both are committed in the
repo — we didn't delete the losses. The 96% only came after we diagnosed why we were losing. If
we were chasing a headline we'd have stopped at run 1, which said 88% on day one.

---

**Q3. "Isn't 96% just because you flag more points?"**

No — that's the entire design of the final test. Each device's budget is set to its own
rolling-sigma flag rate, so the model may raise exactly as many alerts as the classical method.
1,039 against 1,023, both 1.9% of rows. Matched budgets mean the difference is detection quality,
not volume. We learned this the hard way — an earlier run hit 84% recall by flagging 90% of rows.

---

**Q4. "This isn't SNMP, you're replaying CSVs."**

Correct, and it's on slide 4. Why: live polling of healthy devices produces no anomalies and no
labels, so we couldn't put an honest number on accuracy. Why it doesn't matter architecturally:
every metric travels under its real SNMP object name through a pluggable collector. Swapping in a
live pysnmp poller changes one class and nothing downstream. The schema is real; only the source
is simulated.

---

**Q5. "Your topology is fake, so blast radius is meaningless."**

The topology is synthetic and we say so up front — no public dataset ships a graph alongside
labelled telemetry. But the logic is real: a graph walk from a failed node to its dependents.
Point it at a real CMDB or LLDP discovery and the same code gives the same answer. We also
disclose that five of the twenty devices are time-offset copies and are excluded from every
recall number.

---

**Q6. "Does this scale to 10,000 devices?"**

Detection is per-device and independent — no cross-device model to retrain, so it parallelises
naturally. The per-device cost is a rolling refit, milliseconds. At that scale the bottleneck is
polling I/O and database writes, which is why scoring is a separate service writing to Postgres
rather than logic in the UI. Honestly: we haven't load-tested it. We scoped 15 devices so we
could validate accuracy properly instead of quoting a scale number nobody had checked.

---

**Q7. "Why Isolation Forest? Why not deep learning?"**

It's a validated baseline, not our final answer — LOF, One-Class SVM and an ensemble are
scheduled before the 31st. On deep learning specifically: an LSTM needs lots of data per device
and, critically, labelled anomalies to train on. We have 25 labelled windows total. That's ground
truth for *evaluation*, nowhere near enough for supervised training. Unsupervised methods that
learn each device's own baseline are the right family here. And the detector is swappable behind
a fixed interface, so the rest of the build never waits on the answer.

---

**Q8. "Your dashboard says 'restart the process.' How does your model know it's a memory leak?"**

It doesn't, and we keep those claims separate on purpose. Our dataset labels anomaly *windows*,
not *causes* — no public dataset labels causes. Detection is validated against ground truth; the
remedy mapping is expert-authored, a twelve-rule table keyed by the shape of the anomaly. Worth
adding: training a cause classifier here would be circular — we'd have to generate the labels
from those same rules, so the model could only reproduce them, never beat them. Detection is
where ML helps; diagnosis is a rule base, which is how Cisco and SolarWinds do it too.

---

**Q9. "What's actually working versus what's a picture?"** ← *answer fast and flatly*

Working: the whole detection pipeline, six scripts, final one at 96% against ground truth,
runnable right now. Topology graph built. The console is working HTML — real markup, not an
image — but not yet wired to live data. Not built: blast radius scoring, forecast, peer
comparison, what-if map, alert suppression. All five designed and scheduled with dates on slide
6. We'd rather show an honest scope than claim a demo we can't run.

---

**Q10. "You miss one window. Which, and why?"**

23 of 24. The miss sits in a low-variance stretch — the anomaly is small relative to that
device's own noise floor, so at a 1.9% budget it doesn't rank in the top flagged points. We could
catch it by widening the budget, but that's exactly the trade we refuse to make silently. It's
also the shape of miss the bakeoff targets: LOF handles local-density anomalies better than
Isolation Forest.

---

### Quick-fire

| Question | Answer |
|---|---|
| Why Supabase? | Postgres with realtime built in, free tier, no infrastructure to manage. Four people, eleven days. |
| Why Next.js? | Realtime, data-dense UI. React Flow and Recharts both need React; Vercel deploys in one step. |
| Is Power BI in the build? | No. Scores land in Postgres so BI tools attach directly. We call that export-ready and claim nothing more. |
| How do you handle false positives? | Matched budgets hold the flag rate at 1.9%, and correlated suppression collapses storms. We don't claim zero — we claim a budget the operator controls. |
| Why is there no feature E? | Our internal register skipped it and we kept the letters stable rather than renumber files mid-build. |
| What if the demo fails on the 31st? | Replay is deterministic — same data, same result, every run. Another reason we chose it over live polling. |
| How is this different from Nagios? | Nagios tells you a device is unhealthy. We rank by what breaks with it, forecast when, and suppress the storm. |
| Who wrote the code? | Split by layer — detection and scoring, database and UI, solution design, topology and QA. Commit history reflects it. |

